>psuedo ftl using a version of an alcubierre drive discovered, but on a cosmic scale is slow
>yeet explorers in ships out to explore newly accessible areas
>protag on a 20 year round-trip venture, cryogenics used for the trip
>finds anomalous signals and freak the fuck out
>turns out a planet inhabited by aliens nuked themselves over a decade ago, small, scattered population remaining
>basically decides to help with what he can before returning to earth to alert everyone else

The story follows two main perspectives, the protag and one of the survivors on the alien planet. I’ve tried my best to keep common sci fi tropes out, or explained them in a way that makes sense. For example, I spent days researching artificial gravity and how it theoretically could work (frame dragging, electromagnetism, etc.), as well as using radioactive beta decay for power in batteries. Translations take time, fabricators aren’t instant and use resources, and the aliens’ biology is completely different to humans, or really anything on Earth.

Of course, as is the thread theme, there will be romance and shenanigans abound, but I also want to in a way teach the reader things that only sci fi can. I’ve had a lot of fun writing it and I hope that at least some anons find it intriguing once I post it

Anonymous Thu 16 Dec 2021 01:49:34 No.43982203 Report
Quoted By: >>43982298
>>43981939
This is a good start, but (I say this even as another amateur myself) you really need to explore more contrast with your shading if you want to add more depth to your pieces. Experiment with not only depth of shadow, but quality of light as well. Shadows aren't typically grey. They're purples, blues, brows, greens, reds. Try blending in some shades of red into dark purples and blues to really make it pop. Hell, try it with green to give it an interesting contrast with the red in the piece.

And use references for christ's sake. This >>43981715
anon is right. You're gimping yourself if you go out of your way to not reference things, and you're only making it harder on yourself while you develop your skills. Use references for line quality, references for lighting, references for posing, references for palettes, references for backgrounds, etc. You get the picture. Practice makes perfect, but you gotta make sure you've perfected your practice. All art is derivative, and there's no shame in letting some other artistic chump take some of the effort off your shoulders.

Wouldn't say they're highly social, anon. In the wild they're situationally social and that's mostly the males. It's not super uncommon for a mammal to get attached to an individual if they raised by them and spent most of their life with them, but that affection sort of border on dependency rather than just being a sweetie. At that point you're either their sole provider or the only constant in their life they got used to. If it's an animal species that used to being in a social structure like wolves, or meerkats etc then you're more likely to get one to seek your comfort in an arguably healthier and natural way.

It reminds me of the silver fox domestication project where they showed ow the most docile foxes respond to human contact versus dogs, and dogs will always be friendlier, more interested in people and outgoing. But it's hard to control for that variable since it's a bit tougher to define.
